{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a4c1204842f7d113", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# data2vec: A General Framework for Self-supervised Learning in Speech, Vision and Language\narXiv: 2202.03555\nAuthors: Alexei Baevski, Wei-Ning Hsu, Qiantong Xu, Arun Babu, Jiatao Gu, Michael Auli\nYear: 2022 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduces data2vec, a unified self-supervised learning framework that uses the same learning objective for speech, vision, and language modalities.\n  2. Proposes a self-distillation setup where a student model predicts contextualized latent representations from an unmasked input encoded by a teacher model with exponentially moving average weights.\n  3. Constructs training targets by averaging the normalized outputs of multiple top Transformer layers from the teacher network, rather than predicting only the final layer.\n  4. Eliminates the need for modality-specific target spaces, such as discrete visual tokens, speech units, or vocabulary words, by regressing continuous and contextualized representations.\n  5. Achieves state-of-the-art or competitive performance across ImageNet-1K image classification, Librispeech speech recognition, and GLUE natural language understanding benchmarks.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散, SSL/多模态\n---\n# LibriTTS: A Corpus Derived from LibriSpeech for Text-to-Speech\narXiv: 1904.02882\nAuthors: Heiga Zen, Viet Dang, Rob Clark, Yu Zhang, Ron J. Weiss, Ye Jia, Zhifeng Chen, Yonghui Wu\nYear: 2019 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduced the LibriTTS corpus, a large 585-hour multi-speaker speech dataset specifically derived from LibriSpeech for text-to-speech applications.\n  2. Provided audio at a 24kHz sampling rate instead of 16kHz to support higher quality speech synthesis.\n  3. Segmented speech at sentence boundaries rather than silence intervals to preserve sentence-level prosody.\n  4. Included both original and normalized text to retain capitalization and punctuation useful for prosody modeling.\n  5. Added contextual information allowing access to neighboring sentences to facilitate inter-sentence prosody learning.\n  6. Filtered out utterances with significant background noise using estimated signal-to-noise ratios.\n  7. Demonstrated that neural TTS models trained on the LibriTTS corpus achieve high mean opinion scores in naturalness, outperforming models trained on the original LibriSpeech corpus.\n\nTags: TTS", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "1e828321-a6e9-41cf-8e6e-030da376db66", "uuid": "60ac3ece-d1fe-4fa1-b5cf-97c075f0d9fc", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T12:14:38.889Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# data2vec: A General Framework for Self-supervised Learning in Speech, Vision and Language\narXiv: 2202.03555\nAuthors: Alexei Baevski, Wei-Ning Hsu, Qiantong Xu, Arun Babu, Jiatao Gu, Michael Auli\nYear: 2022 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduces data2vec, a unified self-supervised learning framework that uses the same learning objective for speech, vision, and language modalities.\n  2. Proposes a self-distillation setup where a student model predicts contextualized latent representations from an unmasked input encoded by a teacher model with exponentially moving average weights.\n  3. Constructs training targets by averaging the normalized outputs of multiple top Transformer layers from the teacher network, rather than predicting only the final layer.\n  4. Eliminates the need for modality-specific target spaces, such as discrete visual tokens, speech units, or vocabulary words, by regressing continuous and contextualized representations.\n  5. Achieves state-of-the-art or competitive performance across ImageNet-1K image classification, Librispeech speech recognition, and GLUE natural language understanding benchmarks.\n\nTags: SSL, SSL/预测式-离散, SSL/多模态\n---\n# LibriTTS: A Corpus Derived from LibriSpeech for Text-to-Speech\narXiv: 1904.02882\nAuthors: Heiga Zen, Viet Dang, Rob Clark, Yu Zhang, Ron J. Weiss, Ye Jia, Zhifeng Chen, Yonghui Wu\nYear: 2019 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduced the LibriTTS corpus, a large 585-hour multi-speaker speech dataset specifically derived from LibriSpeech for text-to-speech applications.\n  2. Provided audio at a 24kHz sampling rate instead of 16kHz to support higher quality speech synthesis.\n  3. Segmented speech at sentence boundaries rather than silence intervals to preserve sentence-level prosody.\n  4. Included both original and normalized text to retain capitalization and punctuation useful for prosody modeling.\n  5. Added contextual information allowing access to neighboring sentences to facilitate inter-sentence prosody learning.\n  6. Filtered out utterances with significant background noise using estimated signal-to-noise ratios.\n  7. Demonstrated that neural TTS models trained on the LibriTTS corpus achieve high mean opinion scores in naturalness, outperforming models trained on the original LibriSpeech corpus.\n\nTags: TTS", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
