{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-90b8d5ec9da56a94", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tCARD: Cross-component Audio Representation\n2\tDistillation for Encoder-Free Audio Captioning\n3\tGanesh Pavan Kartikeya Bharadwaj Kolluri1 , Yuchen Zhang1,2 , Michael Kampouridis1 , Ravi Shekhar1,2\n4\t\n5\tarXiv:2607.04619v1 [cs.SD] 6 Jul 2026\n6\t\n7\t1\n8\t\n9\tSchool of Computer Science and Electronic Engineering, University of Essex\n10\t2\n11\tInstitute for Analytics and Data Science, University of Essex\n12\t{karthik.kolluri, yuchen.zhang, mkampo, r.shekhar}@essex.ac.uk\n13\t\n14\tAbstract—Modern automated audio captioning systems pair\n15\ta frozen audio encoder with a large language model (LLM)\n16\tvia a trainable projector, incurring the encoder’s inference cost\n17\tand bottlenecking the model through its fixed acoustic features.\n18\tWe present CARD, an encoder-free audio captioning model that\n19\tremoves the encoder at inference: a 13.2M projector feeds a\n20\tfrozen LLM with merged LoRA adapters, while the teacher used\n21\tto train it is discarded. CARD distills a pretrained audio teacher\n22\t(CLAP-HTSAT) into the model, but rather than injecting it into\n23\tthe LLM alone, it routes the teacher’s representations across\n24\tcomponents: perceptual stages to the projector and semantic\n25\tstages to the LLM. This placement improves CIDEr-D by +12.18\n26\tover an LLM-only distilled model on AudioCaps and by +5.21 on\n27\tClotho, reaching 55.4 against a 66.4 encoder-kept upper bound\n28\twith no encoder at inference, showing that where a teacher’s\n29\tknowledge is placed matters as much as its presence.\n30\tIndex Terms—audio captioning, encoder-free models, crosscomponent distillation, audio-language models.\n31\t\n32\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n33\tAutomated audio captioning (AAC) is the task of generating\n34\ta natural-language description of the sound events in an audio\n35\tclip, such as “rain falls as thunder rumbles in the distance.”\n36\tUnlike automatic speech recognition (ASR), which transcribes\n37\tspoken words from the speech audio, AAC aims to describe\n38\tthe broader acoustic scene, capturing non-speech sounds and\n39\ttheir relationships in free-form natural language. This ability\n40\tto summarize what an audio clip contains has made AAC\n41\tvaluable for applications such as accessibility, audio retrieval,\n42\tand content understanding [1], [2].\n43\tMost recent AAC systems follow a common architectural\n44\tdesign: A frozen pre-trained audio encoder, such as CLAP [3],\n45\tfirst converts the raw audio clip into a sequence of acoustic\n46\tfeature vectors. A trainable projector then maps these features\n47\tinto the input space of the Large Language Model (LLM),\n48\twhich decodes them into a caption. Since both the audio\n49\tencoder and the LLM are pre-trained separately and usually\n50\tkept frozen, only the projector is trained to bridge the two\n51\tcomponents together. This design has been widely adopted\n52\tbecause it inherits the strengths of a powerful audio encoder\n53\tand a capable language model while learning little more\n54\tthan the alignment between them [4]–[6]. Its main limitation,\n55\thowever, is that inference still depends on the dedicated\n56\taudio encoder. Every clip must pass through a full encoder\n57\tforward pass before the language model can act, which adds\n58\tcomputation and memory, and confines the language model to\n59\tperceiving audio only through the encoder’s fixed features.\n60\t\n61\tA natural way to remove this dependency is to discard the\n62\taudio encoder from the pipeline and let the model caption\n63\taudio on its own. However, without the encoder, the projector\n64\tand the language model must learn to perceive audio directly\n65\tfrom the raw acoustic signal, rather than building on representations from a model already trained on large amounts\n66\tof audio. Learning to extract useful acoustic features from\n67\tscratch, while at the same time learning to generate captions,\n68\tplaces a much heavier burden on training and tends to be\n69\tunstable. For this reason, encoder-free models have generally\n70\tstruggled to reach the performance of their encoder-based\n71\tcounterparts [7], [8].\n72\tA promising way to ease this difficulty is knowledge distillation. Instead of learning to perceive audio entirely from\n73\tscratch, the model can be guided during training by a pretrained encoder acting as a teacher, and this teacher is then discarded at inference, so the model retains the teacher’s knowledge without paying its runtime cost [8]. Existing approaches,\n74\thowever, distill the teacher almost entirely into the language\n75\tmodel, while the projector receives no representation-level\n76\tsupervision [9]. This is particularly important for audio captioning because the projector is responsible for converting\n77\tthe acoustic signal into the audio tokens consumed by the\n78\tlanguage model. Unlike the language model, however, it\n79\treceives no direct representation-level supervision and must\n80\tinstead learn solely from the captioning objective. This raises a\n81\tquestion that prior work has not examined. Rather than asking\n82\twhether to distill, we ask how teacher knowledge should be\n83\tdistributed across the components of an encoder-free AAC\n84\tmodel.\n85\tWe address this question with CARD, a cross-component\n86\tdistillation framework for encoder-free audio captioning. The\n87\tcentral idea is to assign teacher representations to student\n88\tcomponents according to their functional roles. Earlier teacher\n89\tlayers provide lower-level acoustic cues for supervising the\n90\taudio projector, while later teacher layers provide more abstract information for supervising the language model. In this\n91\tway, the projector learns to form audio tokens from lowlevel acoustic supervision, and the language model learns\n92\tto interpret them with higher-level semantic supervision. At\n93\tinference, the teacher and all distillation heads are removed,\n94\tand the LoRA adapters are merged into the base model. The\n95\tdeployed model contains only the audio projector and the\n96\tlanguage model, with no audio encoder.\n97\t\n98\t\fOur contributions are as follows:\n99\t• We propose CARD, an encoder-free model for audio\n100\tcaptioning that removes the audio encoder at inference\n101\tthrough teacher-guided distillation, leaving only a frozen,\n102\tLoRA-adapted language model and an audio projector.\n103\t•\n104\t\n105\tWe introduce the cross-component distillation framework, which assigns the teacher’s early representations\n106\tto the audio projector and its later representations to the\n107\tlanguage model, matching each component to the level\n108\tof knowledge it is best suited to learn.\n109\t\n110\t•\n111\t\n112\tWe provide comprehensive experiments showing that\n113\tthe placement of teacher supervision is critical for\n114\tencoder-free AAC, and that CARD substantially outperforms LLM-only distillation strategies that supervise the\n115\tlanguage model alone.\n116\tII. R ELATED W ORK\n117\t\n118\tA. Encoder-based automated audio captioning\n119\tRecent LLM-based AAC systems mostly share a common\n120\tarchitectural design, in which a frozen pretrained audio encoder first extracts acoustic representations, and a trainable\n121\tprojector subsequently aligns these representations with a language decoder. EnCLAP [4] employs a frozen CLAP encoder\n122\ttogether with a BART decoder. DRCap [6] further incorporates\n123\tretrieval-augmented prompting, while SLAM-AAC [5] couples\n124\tthe EAT encoder with an LLM through a lightweight projector.\n125\tLOAE [10] follows a similar design using the CED [11]\n126\tencoder.\n127\tThese systems have demonstrated strong captioning performance. However, maintaining a separate audio encoder\n128\tintroduces several limitations. First, the encoder remains active\n129\tduring inference, increasing computational and memory requirements beyond the language model itself [12]. Second, the\n130\tlanguage model is restricted to operating within the encoder’s\n131\tfrozen representation space, making acoustic information discarded by the encoder inaccessible downstream [8], [13].\n132\tThird, bridging pretrained audio encoders and language models commonly relies on training a projector on paired audio–\n133\ttext data to align encoder outputs with the language model\n134\tembedding space [4], [5]. These considerations motivate the\n135\tquestion of whether the audio encoder can be removed entirely.\n136\tB. Encoder-free audio-language models\n137\tEncoder-free multimodal large language models aim to internalize modality understanding directly within the language\n138\tmodel, eliminating the need for dedicated modality encoders\n139\tat inference time. This paradigm was first explored in the\n140\tvision domain, where Fuyu-8B [13], EVE [7], and MonoInternVL [14] demonstrated that visual representations can\n141\tbe learned within an LLM through lightweight projections\n142\tof raw image inputs, while VoRA [8] further introduced\n143\tteacher-guided distillation as an alternative route to encoderfree adaptation.\n144\tSuch encoder-free designs have only recently begun to be\n145\texplored for audio understanding. Early studies mainly rely\n146\t\n147\ton downstream supervision to induce acoustic understanding\n148\twithin an LLM. Mel-LLM [12] projects Mel-spectrogram\n149\tpatches through a linear projector into a LoRA-adapted LLM\n150\tand learns acoustic representations from speech-oriented tasks\n151\tsuch as ASR and Text to Speech (TTS), without explicit\n152\trepresentational supervision. Gemma4-12B [15] follows a\n153\tsimilar philosophy at a larger scale by removing dedicated\n154\taudio encoders altogether and projecting raw audio directly\n155\tinto the LLM, again without supervision of the audio frontend.\n156\tMore recently, AuRA [9], concurrent with our work, introduced teacher-guided adaptation for encoder-free audio understanding. It distills a frozen ASR encoder into a LoRA-adapted\n157\tLLM through layer-wise hidden-state alignment. Its supervision, however, is applied entirely on the language-model side,\n158\tleaving the audio frontend unsupervised. Moreover, AuRA\n159\tfocuses on speech-oriented tasks such as transcription, whereas\n160\tAAC requires recognizing and describing diverse environmental and non-speech acoustic events in natural language.\n161\tTogether, these studies demonstrate that audio understanding can be internalized into an LLM. Existing approaches\n162\tdiffer primarily in how acoustic knowledge is acquired. MelLLM and Gemma 4 rely solely on downstream objectives\n163\tto induce acoustic representations, whereas AuRA introduces\n164\tsupervision from a pretrained teacher. However, even in the\n165\tlatter case, supervision is applied only to language-model\n166\tlayers, leaving the audio frontend that first transforms raw\n167\tsignals into tokens unsupervised. Consequently, the question\n168\tof where teacher knowledge should be injected within an\n169\tencoder-free audio–LLM remains largely unexplored.\n170\tC. Distillation for encoder-free multimodal models\n171\tKnowledge distillation [16] transfers information from\n172\ta teacher model to a student model through output- or\n173\trepresentation-level supervision. In the LLM era, distillation\n174\thas evolved from a model compression technique into a\n175\tmechanism that enables encoder-free multimodal adaptation,\n176\tallowing modality-specific knowledge to be internalized into\n177\tlanguage models without retaining dedicated encoders at inference [17].\n178\tRecent approaches mainly employ distillation strategies\n179\tbased on hidden-state alignment. VoRA [8] distills a frozen\n180\tvision transformer into LoRA adapters inserted within an\n181\tLLM via block-wise supervision, after which the adapters are\n182\tmerged and the teacher discarded. AuRA [9] adopts a similar\n183\tstrategy for speech, aligning hidden representations from a\n184\tfrozen ASR encoder with LoRA-adapted language layers. In\n185\tthis view, distillation is not merely a compression technique\n186\tapplied after architectural design, but the mechanism by which\n187\tan encoder-free architecture becomes achievable.\n188\tDespite their effectiveness, existing cross-modal distillation\n189\tmethods inject supervision into a single class of locations\n190\twithin the student, typically the language-model blocks, while\n191\ttreating the modality frontend as an unsupervised projection.\n192\tConsequently, whether teacher knowledge should instead be\n193\tdistributed across multiple components of an encoder-free\n194\t\n195\t\faudio–LLM according to their distinct functional roles remains\n196\tunexplored.\n197\tIII. M ETHODOLOGY\n198\tCARD is an audio captioning model that eliminates the need\n199\tfor a dedicated audio encoder. Unlike conventional architectures [5] that rely on a pretrained audio encoder, projector,\n200\tand LLM decoder, CARD learns acoustic knowledge through\n201\trepresentation-level distillation from a frozen teacher model.\n202\tThe student model consists only of a audio projector and a\n203\tLoRA-adapted LLM. After training, the teacher is removed,\n204\tand the LoRA adapters are merged into the LLM, resulting\n205\tin an efficient architecture comprising only the LLM backbone and audio projector while maintaining audio-captioning\n206\tcapability. The overview of CARD is shown in Figure 1.\n207\tA. Model Architecture\n208\tStudent model. The student model consists of a lightweight\n209\taudio projector followed by a LoRA-adapted large language\n210\tmodel. Given an input audio clip, the projector converts the\n211\taudio into a sequence of audio tokens, which are prepended\n212\tto the text prompt embeddings and consumed by the language\n213\tmodel to generate the output caption.\n214\tSpecifically, the audio is first resampled to 48 kHz and\n215\tconverted into a 64-band log-Mel spectrogram using the CLAP\n216\tprocessor [3]. The audio projector consists of a stack of strided\n217\tone-dimensional convolutional layers, followed by a linear\n218\tprojection to the LLM hidden size and layer normalization.\n219\tThe output is a sequence of audio tokens used as the prefix to\n220\tthe language model. The resulting audio-token sequence forms\n221\tthe prefix presented to the language model.\n222\tWe adopt Qwen3-4B [18] as the language backbone. Adaptation is performed using LoRA [19] on the linear layers\n223\tof every transformer block, including the query, key, value,\n224\toutput, gate, up, and down projections. All other parameters\n225\tare frozen, so only the LoRA parameters are optimized during\n226\ttraining. After training, the LoRA weights are merged into the\n227\tbackbone, introducing no additional parameters or computational overhead at inference.\n228\tTeacher model. We employ a frozen CLAP [20] as the\n229\tteacher throughout training. CLAP is contrastively pretrained\n230\ton paired audio–text data and serves as the audio encoder\n231\tin several state-of-the-art AAC systems [4], [6]. Its representations therefore provide caption-relevant acoustic knowledge\n232\tfor supervising the student model.\n233\tThe CLAP audio branch adopts an HTSAT backbone [21],\n234\timplemented as a hierarchical Swin Transformer [22]. The\n235\tbackbone produces a hierarchy of intermediate representations\n236\twith progressively increasing semantic abstraction. During\n237\ttraining, the teacher receives the same log-Mel spectrogram\n238\tas the student. The resulting intermediate representations are\n239\tused as supervision signals in the component-aware distillation\n240\tdescribed next.\n241\t\n242\tB. Cross Component Distillation\n243\tIn existing teacher-guided encoder-free audio models [9],\n244\tteacher supervision is typically applied only to languagemodel layers, leaving the audio projector trained solely\n245\tthrough the downstream captioning objective. Since every\n246\taudio token consumed by the language model is produced\n247\tby the projector, insufficient supervision at the projector may\n248\tlimit the quality of all downstream representations.\n249\tCARD addresses this mismatch by aligning the teacher\n250\thierarchy with the functional structure of the student. The\n251\tCLAP teacher provides acoustic representations at multiple\n252\tlevels of abstraction through its hierarchical HTSAT backbone.\n253\tThe student, in contrast, separates computation across two\n254\tcomponents: the projector transforms raw acoustic signals into\n255\tlanguage-compatible representations, and the language model\n256\tinterprets these representations for semantic reasoning and\n257\tcaption generation. Teacher supervision is therefore assigned\n258\taccording to component function, with lower-level acoustic\n259\trepresentations supervising the projector and higher-level semantic representations supervising the language model.\n260\tSpecifically, we extract the outputs of the four HTSAT\n261\tstages, {t0 , t1 , t2 , t3 }, as teacher representations. Since the\n262\tsemantic abstraction of these representations increases with\n263\tnetwork depth, we use the earlier stages to supervise the audio\n264\tprojector and the later stages to supervise the language model.\n265\tFor projector supervision, the audio projector produces a\n266\tsingle sequence of audio tokens. Let uproj denote the meanpooled projector representation. We attach one linear distillation head for t0 and another for t1 , both operating on the same\n267\tmean-pooled projector representation:\n268\tû0 = W0 uproj ,\n269\t\n270\tû1 = W1 uproj .\n271\t\n272\t(1)\n273\t\n274\tThe projected representations û0 and û1 are then matched to\n275\tthe mean-pooled teacher features from t0 and t1 using cosinebased distillation.\n276\tFor language-model supervision, we use the hidden representations at the audio-token positions from the lower 12 transformer blocks. Let u1llm denote the average representation over\n277\tblocks 0–8, and let u2llm denote the average representation over\n278\tblocks 9–11. Two linear distillation heads then project these\n279\trepresentations to the dimensionalities of the corresponding\n280\tteacher stages:\n281\tû2 = W2 u1llm ,\n282\t\n283\tû3 = W3 u2llm .\n284\t\n285\t(2)\n286\t\n287\tSimilarly, the projected representations û2 and û3 are compared with the corresponding teacher representations t2 and t3\n288\tusing the cosine distillation loss. The remaining transformer\n289\tblocks are not directly supervised by the teacher and are\n290\toptimized only through the captioning objective.\n291\tThe pairwise distillation loss for each teacher–student representation pair is defined as\n292\tℓdistill (ûi , ti ) = 1 − cos(ûi , ti ),\n293\t\n294\t(3)\n295\t\n296\twhere i ∈ {0, 1, 2, 3} indexes the four teacher stages, and\n297\tûi and ti denote the projected student representation and the\n298\tcorresponding teacher representation, respectively.\n299\t\n300\t\fCARD Training Pipeline\n301\t\n302\tCARD Inference Pipeline\n303\tCaption: \"A dog is barking\"\n304\t\n305\tCLAP (Teacher)\n306\t\n307\tSemantic Distillation\n308\t\n309\tLLM\n310\t\n311\tCaption: \"Rain falls and thunder rumbles\"\n312\t\n313\tDistill\n314\tloss\n315\t\n316\tAux head\n317\t\n318\tLoRA\n319\t\n320\tBlocks 12-35\n321\t\n322\tDistill\n323\tloss\n324\t\n325\tAux head\n326\t\n327\tLoRA\n328\t\n329\tBlocks 9-11\n330\t\n331\tDistill\n332\tloss\n333\t\n334\tLoRA\n335\t\n336\tBlocks 0-8\n337\t\n338\tMLP head\n339\t\n340\t(LM loss only)\n341\t\n342\tStage 3\n343\t768-d, semantic\n344\t\n345\tLLM\n346\tLoRA (Merged)\n347\t\n348\tStage 2\n349\t768-d, semantic\n350\t\n351\tStage 1\n352\t384-d, perceptual\n353\t\n354\tAudio Projector\n355\t\n356\tTokenizer\n357\tCLAP audio frontend\n358\t\n359\tStage 0\n360\t192-d, perceptual\n361\t\n362\tDistill\n363\tloss\n364\t\n365\tMLP head\n366\t\n367\tAudio Projector\n368\t\n369\tRaw audio\n370\t\n371\tTokenizer\n372\t\n373\tPerceptual Distillation\n374\t\n375\tPrompt: \"Describe the audio\"\n376\t\n377\tCLAP audio frontend\n378\t\n379\tCLAP audio frontend\n380\t\n381\tPrompt: \"Describe the audio\"\n382\tRaw audio\n383\tRaw audio\n384\t\n385\tTrainable\n386\t\n387\tAudio hidden state\n388\t\n389\tMel-spectogram\n390\t\n391\tFrozen\n392\t\n393\tText hidden state\n394\t\n395\tTeacher hidden state\n396\t\n397\tFig. 1. Overview of CARD. During training (left), a frozen CLAP teacher supervises the two student components by role: its early, perceptual stages (0-1)\n398\tdistill into the audio projector, and its later, semantic stages (2-3) into the LLM’s LoRA adapters. At inference (right), the teacher and distillation heads are\n399\tdropped, and the LoRA is merged into the LLM, leaving only the projector and the LLM, with no audio encoder.\n400\t\n401\tC. Training Objective\n402\tCARD is trained in two consecutive phases with different\n403\toptimization objectives. During Phase 1, the student model\n404\tis jointly optimized with a captioning loss, Lcap , a projector\n405\tdistillation loss, Lproj , and a language-model distillation loss,\n406\tLllm , while the CLAP teacher remains frozen. The audio\n407\tprojector, LoRA adapters, and distillation heads are jointly\n408\tupdated to transfer caption-relevant acoustic knowledge from\n409\tthe teacher into the encoder-free student. After Phase 1, the\n410\tteacher model and all distillation heads are removed.\n411\tSpecifically, the projector distillation loss is obtained by\n412\taveraging the pairwise distillation losses associated with the\n413\tlower teacher stages,\n414\t1\n415\tLproj = (ℓdistill (û0 , t0 ) + ℓdistill (û1 , t1 )) .\n416\t(4)\n417\t2\n418\tThe language-model distillation loss is computed from the\n419\thigher teacher stages,\n420\t1\n421\t(ℓdistill (û2 , t2 ) + ℓdistill (û3 , t3 )) .\n422\t(5)\n423\t2\n424\tThe captioning loss is the standard autoregressive crossentropy loss over the target caption tokens,\n425\tLllm =\n426\t\n427\tLcap = −\n428\t\n429\tN\n430\tX\n431\t\n432\tlog p(yi | y<i , x),\n433\t\n434\t(6)\n435\t\n436\ti=1\n437\t\n438\twhere x denotes the input audio tokens and y = {y1 , . . . , yN }\n439\tis the target caption.\n440\tThe overall training objective during Phase 1 is\n441\tLphase1 = Lcap + λproj Lproj + λllm Lllm ,\n442\t\n443\t(7)\n444\t\n445\twhere λproj = λllm = 1 in all experiments. The teacher\n446\tmodel and all distillation heads are used only during training\n447\t\n448\tand are discarded afterwards. At inference, only the audio\n449\tprojector and the LoRA-merged language model are retained.\n450\tDuring Phase 2, the student model is fine-tuned separately\n451\tfor each evaluation dataset using only the captioning loss Lcap ,\n452\tallowing the model to adapt to the target caption distribution\n453\twithout additional teacher supervision:\n454\tLphase2 = Lcap .\n455\t\n456\t(8)\n457\t\n458\tAfter Phase 2, the LoRA adapters are merged into the\n459\tlanguage-model backbone, yielding the final deployed model\n460\twith only the lightweight audio projector and the language\n461\tmodel.\n462\tIV. E XPERIMENTS\n463\tA. Experimental Setting\n464\tDatasets. Table I summarizes the datasets used in the\n465\ttwo training phases. Phase 1 uses a large-scale mixture of\n466\tcaptioned-audio datasets for representation learning, including\n467\tWavCaps [23], Auto-ACD [24], AudioCaps [1], Clotho [2],\n468\tand MACS [25]. To preserve the language understanding\n469\tcapability of the backbone LLM, text-only instruction data\n470\tfrom Infinity-Instruct [26] are interleaved during training.\n471\tPhase 2 fine-tunes the pretrained student separately for\n472\teach evaluation benchmark, following the two-stage setup of\n473\tSLAM-AAC [5]: For AudioCaps evaluation, the model is finetuned on the prompt-expanded AudioCaps training set [1],\n474\twhile Clotho evaluation uses the corresponding promptexpanded Clotho training set [2]. We evaluate on the standard\n475\tAudioCaps and Clotho benchmarks.\n476\tImplementation details. CARD uses Qwen3-4B [18] as\n477\tthe language backbone and CLAP [20] as the Phase 1 teacher.\n478\tThe CLAP teacher is kept frozen throughout training. LoRA\n479\tis applied to all seven linear projections of all 36 transformer\n480\t\n481\t\fB. Overall Results\n482\t\n483\tTABLE I\n484\tDATASET S UMMARY.\n485\t\n486\tPhase\n487\t\n488\tDataset\n489\t\n490\tSamples\n491\t\n492\tPhase 1\n493\t\n494\tWavCaps [23]\n495\tAuto-ACD [24]\n496\tAudioCaps [1]\n497\tClotho [2]\n498\tMACS [25]\n499\tText-instruction mix\n500\t\n501\t140,750\n502\t82,268\n503\t45,178\n504\t3,839\n505\t3,930\n506\t50,000\n507\t\n508\tPhase 2\n509\t\n510\tAudioCaps\n511\tClotho\n512\t\n513\t225,890\n514\t95,975\n515\t\n516\tEvaluation\n517\t\n518\tAudioCaps test\n519\tClotho evaluation\n520\t\n521\t975\n522\t1,045\n523\t\n524\tblocks of Qwen3-4B. The audio projector consists of two\n525\tstrided 1-D convolutional layers with kernel size 3 and GELU\n526\tactivations. The first and second convolutional layers project\n527\tthe 64-channel Mel spectrogram to 512 and 2560 channels,\n528\trespectively.\n529\tPhase 1 optimizes the audio projector, LoRA adapters, and\n530\tdistillation heads for one epoch. Optimization is performed\n531\tusing AdamW with β = (0.9, 0.95), an effective batch size of\n532\t64, an initial learning rate of 2×10−4 , a constant-with-warmup\n533\tlearning-rate schedule, and gradient clipping with a maximum\n534\tnorm of 1.0. LoRA is configured with rank r = 16 and scaling\n535\tfactor α = 16. Text-only instruction examples are interleaved\n536\tas modality-pure batches, where audio and text examples are\n537\tnot mixed within a batch.\n538\tIn Phase 2, the teacher and all distillation heads are removed, and the model is fine-tuned for captioning on the target\n539\tdataset without distillation. A fresh LoRA adapter (r=16,\n540\tα=16) is then trained on this consolidated backbone for one\n541\tepoch, while the projector continues from its Phase 1 checkpoint. Building captioning on top of the merged backbone lets\n542\tPhase 2 specialize while leaving the Phase 1 alignment intact.\n543\tAt evaluation, captions are generated using beam search\n544\twith a beam size of 4 and a maximum length of 40 tokens.\n545\tAll experiments are conducted on 2×A6000 GPUs with 48 GB\n546\tmemory each.\n547\tBaselines. We use SLAM-AAC as the encoder-based baseline. For a fair comparison, we replace its original audio encoder with the same CLAP encoder used in our teacher model.\n548\tWe report two settings, without LoRA and with LoRA, both\n549\tof which retain the frozen CLAP encoder during inference.\n550\tMetrics. We use CIDEr-D (CD) [27] as the primary\n551\tmetric, as it measures consensus with human references and is\n552\twidely reported in AAC benchmarks. We also report SPIDEr\n553\t(SD) [28], SPICE (SC) [29], METEOR (MT) [30] to provide\n554\ta comprehensive assessment of caption quality.\n555\t\n556\tTable II compares audio captioning performance on the\n557\tAudioCaps and Clotho benchmarks between the encoderbased SLAM-AAC baseline and the proposed CARD framework. Within CARD, we compare several distillation configurations. No Distill removes teacher supervision entirely.\n558\tLLM Distill applies teacher supervision only to the language model. Proj Full applies teacher supervision only to\n559\tthe audio projector, using teacher representations from all\n560\tfour HTSAT stages, {t0 , t1 , t2 , t3 }. Proj Early also supervises\n561\tonly the audio projector, but uses only the early teacher\n562\tstages t0 , t1 . CARD⋄ combines full-stage projector supervision\n563\twith language-model supervision. CARD∗ combines earlystage projector supervision with language-model supervision,\n564\tcorresponding to the projector supervision described in Section III-B.\n565\tEncoder-based baseline. The encoder-based SLAM-AAC\n566\tbaseline achieves the strongest overall performance. With\n567\tLoRA, it reaches 66.4% CIDEr-D on AudioCaps and 39.0% on\n568\tClotho. This is expected because the CLAP encoder is retained\n569\tduring inference and directly provides acoustic representations\n570\tto the language model.\n571\tEffect of distillation placement. Removing the encoder\n572\tleads to a substantial performance drop. Without teacher supervision, No Distill achieves 43.2% CIDEr-D on AudioCaps\n573\tand 22.3% on Clotho. Applying teacher supervision only to\n574\tthe language model gives almost no improvement, with LLM\n575\tDistill reaching 43.5% and 22.5%, respectively. This suggests\n576\tthat language-model supervision alone cannot compensate for\n577\tthe absence of direct supervision on the audio projector.\n578\tProjector supervision is more effective, but only when\n579\tthe teacher representation matches the role of the projector. Proj Full reaches 40.7% CIDEr-D on AudioCaps, while\n580\tProj Early improves this to 52.5%. The same trend appears on\n581\tClotho, where Proj Early improves over Proj Full by 3.1%.\n582\tThis shows that the projector benefits more from early-stage\n583\tteacher representations than from the full teacher hierarchy.\n584\tFull CARD model. Combining projector and languagemodel supervision gives the best encoder-free results. CARD⋄\n585\treaches 49.9% CIDEr-D on AudioCaps, while CARD∗ reaches\n586\t55.4%. On Clotho, CARD∗ also achieves the best encoderfree result, reaching 27.5% CIDEr-D. Compared with No\n587\tDistill, CARD∗ improves CIDEr-D by 12.2 percentage points\n588\ton AudioCaps and 5.2 percentage points on Clotho, with\n589\tconsistent gains across SPIDEr, SPICE, and METEOR.\n590\tOverall, the results show that teacher supervision is most\n591\teffective when early teacher representations supervise the\n592\taudio projector and later teacher representations supervise the\n593\tlanguage model. This supports the component-aware distillation strategy used in CARD∗ .\n594\tC. Model Analysis\n595\tEffect of LoRA Capacity. Table III studies the effect of\n596\tLoRA capacity under different training settings. With crosscomponent distillation, the model is sensitive to the LoRA\n597\trank. Using rank 8 gives 33.3% CIDEr-D on AudioCaps and\n598\t\n599\t\fTABLE II\n600\tAUDIO CAPTIONING PERFORMANCE ON THE AUDIO C APS AND C LOTHO EVALUATION SPLITS . A LL VALUES ARE REPORTED AS PERCENTAGES (%).\n601\t\n602\tModel\n603\t\n604\tSLAM–AAC\n605\t\n606\tCARD\n607\t\n608\tVariant\n609\t\n610\tEnc.\n611\t\n612\tLoRA\n613\t\n614\tCD\n615\t\n616\tSD\n617\t\n618\tSC\n619\t\n620\tMT\n621\t\n622\tCD\n623\t\n624\tSD\n625\t\n626\tSC\n627\t\n628\tMT\n629\t\n630\t✓\n631\t✓\n632\t\n633\t✗\n634\t✓\n635\t\n636\t–\n637\t–\n638\t\n639\t59.8\n640\t66.4\n641\t\n642\t38.7\n643\t41.9\n644\t\n645\t17.5\n646\t17.3\n647\t\n648\t23.7\n649\t23.3\n650\t\n651\t32.0\n652\t39.0\n653\t\n654\t22.3\n655\t25.8\n656\t\n657\t12.2\n658\t12.7\n659\t\n660\t16.4\n661\t16.2\n662\t\n663\tNo Distill\n664\tLLM Distill\n665\t\n666\t✗\n667\t✗\n668\t\n669\t✓\n670\t✓\n671\t\n672\tNo teacher\n673\tLLM only\n674\t\n675\t43.2\n676\t43.5\n677\t\n678\t27.9\n679\t27.8\n680\t\n681\t12.6\n682\t12.2\n683\t\n684\t18.4\n685\t18.4\n686\t\n687\t22.3\n688\t22.5\n689\t\n690\t15.5\n691\t15.1\n692\t\n693\t8.6\n694\t8.4\n695\t\n696\t13.0\n697\t13.0\n698\t\n699\tProj Full\n700\tProj Early\n701\t\n702\t✗\n703\t✗\n704\t\n705\t✓\n706\t✓\n707\t\n708\tAll stages→projector\n709\tEarly stages→Projector\n710\t\n711\t40.7\n712\t52.5\n713\t\n714\t26.4\n715\t33.3\n716\t\n717\t12.1\n718\t14.1\n719\t\n720\t17.8\n721\t20.1\n722\t\n723\t21.2\n724\t24.3\n725\t\n726\t14.6\n727\t16.6\n728\t\n729\t8.1\n730\t8.9\n731\t\n732\t12.7\n733\t13.1\n734\t\n735\tCARD⋄\n736\t\n737\t✗\n738\t\n739\t✓\n740\t\n741\tProjector (all stages) + LLM\n742\t\n743\t49.9\n744\t\n745\t32.0\n746\t\n747\t14.1\n748\t\n749\t20.3\n750\t\n751\t24.8\n752\t\n753\t17.1\n754\t\n755\t9.4\n756\t\n757\t13.1\n758\t\n759\t∗\n760\t\n761\t✗\n762\t\n763\t✓\n764\t\n765\tProjector (early stages) + LLM\n766\t\n767\t55.4\n768\t\n769\t35.2\n770\t\n771\t15.1\n772\t\n773\t21.2\n774\t\n775\t27.5\n776\t\n777\t18.8\n778\t\n779\t10.1\n780\t\n781\t14.2\n782\t\n783\t17.8% on Clotho, below the No Distill setting at rank 16. This\n784\tsuggests that the adapter capacity is insufficient for jointly\n785\tfitting the captioning and distillation objectives. Increasing the\n786\trank to 16 gives the best results on both datasets, reaching\n787\t55.4% on AudioCaps and 27.5% on Clotho. Increasing the\n788\trank further to 32 reduces performance to 50.0% and 24.9%,\n789\tshowing that larger adapters do not necessarily improve transfer.\n790\tThis sensitivity is much weaker without cross-component\n791\tdistillation. Under LLM Distill, increasing α from 16 to 32\n792\treduces CIDEr-D from 43.5% to 41.4% on AudioCaps and\n793\tfrom 22.5% to 20.8% on Clotho. Without teacher supervision,\n794\tincreasing the LoRA rank from 16 to 32 changes CIDEr-D\n795\tonly slightly, from 43.2% to 43.9% on AudioCaps and from\n796\t22.3% to 22.6% on Clotho. These results suggest that LoRA\n797\tcapacity matters most when the adapter must accommodate\n798\tboth the captioning objective and the cross-component teacher\n799\tsignal.\n800\tTABLE III\n801\tE FFECT OF L O RA RANK AND SCALING ON CIDE R -D UNDER DIFFERENT\n802\tDISTILLATION SETTINGS .\n803\tVariant\n804\tCARD∗\n805\tCARD\n806\t\n807\tClotho\n808\t\n809\tNo LoRA\n810\tLoRA\n811\t\n812\tCARD\n813\t\n814\tModel\n815\t\n816\tAudioCaps\n817\t\n818\tDistill\n819\t\n820\tLLM Distill\n821\tNo Distill\n822\t\n823\tTABLE IV\n824\tE FFECT OF THE TWO TRAINING PHASES AT r = 16.\n825\t\n826\tAudioCaps\n827\t\n828\tSetting\n829\tPhase 2 Only\n830\tPhase 1 Only\n831\tPhase 1+2\n832\t\n833\tClotho\n834\t\n835\tCD\n836\t\n837\tSD\n838\t\n839\tSC\n840\t\n841\tMT\n842\t\n843\tCD\n844\t\n845\tSD\n846\t\n847\tSC\n848\t\n849\tMT\n850\t\n851\t37.2\n852\t10.3\n853\t55.4\n854\t\n855\t24.2\n856\t10.6\n857\t35.2\n858\t\n859\t11.2\n860\t11.0\n861\t15.1\n862\t\n863\t17.2\n864\t16.2\n865\t21.2\n866\t\n867\t16.5\n868\t6.3\n869\t27.5\n870\t\n871\t13.3\n872\t6.2\n873\t18.8\n874\t\n875\t6.8\n876\t6.0\n877\t10.1\n878\t\n879\t12.1\n880\t11.2\n881\t14.2\n882\t\n883\tThe full two-stage training pipeline performs best across\n884\tall reported metrics. It reaches 55.4% CIDEr-D, 35.2% SPIDEr, 15.1% SPICE, and 21.2% METEOR on AudioCaps. On\n885\tClotho, it reaches 27.5% CIDEr-D, 18.8% SPIDEr, 10.1%\n886\tSPICE, and 14.2% METEOR. Compared with Phase 2 alone,\n887\tthe full pipeline improves CIDEr-D by 18.2 percentage points\n888\ton AudioCaps and 11.0 points on Clotho. Compared with\n889\tPhase 1 alone, the gains are much larger. These results show\n890\tthat the two phases are complementary. Phase 1 transfers\n891\tacoustic knowledge from the teacher, while Phase 2 adapts\n892\tthe student for caption generation.\n893\t\n894\tr\n895\t\n896\tα\n897\t\n898\tAudioCaps\n899\t\n900\tClotho\n901\t\n902\tV. C ONCLUSION\n903\t\n904\t8\n905\t16\n906\t32\n907\t16\n908\t16\n909\t16\n910\t32\n911\t\n912\t8\n913\t16\n914\t32\n915\t16\n916\t32\n917\t16\n918\t32\n919\t\n920\t33.3\n921\t55.4\n922\t50.0\n923\t43.5\n924\t41.4\n925\t43.2\n926\t43.9\n927\t\n928\t17.8\n929\t27.5\n930\t24.9\n931\t22.5\n932\t20.8\n933\t22.3\n934\t22.6\n935\t\n936\tWe presented CARD, an encoder-free framework for automated audio captioning. CARD transfers acoustic knowledge\n937\tfrom a frozen CLAP teacher into a lightweight audio projector\n938\tand a LoRA-adapted LLM during training. Our results show\n939\tthat knowledge distillation is important for recovering the\n940\tperformance lost by removing the audio encoder, but its\n941\teffectiveness depends strongly on where teacher supervision\n942\tis applied. LLM-only distillation gives negligible gains over\n943\tthe non-distilled encoder-free model, while projector-only distillation with the full teacher hierarchy degrades performance.\n944\tIn contrast, supervising the projector with early teacher stages\n945\tsubstantially improves performance, showing that the projector\n946\tbenefits most from lower-level acoustic representations. The\n947\tfull CARD model combines early-stage projector supervision\n948\twith later-stage language-model supervision and achieves the\n949\t\n950\tEffect of Two-Phase Training. Table IV evaluates the contribution of the two training phases. Using only Phase 2 finetuning achieves 37.2% CIDEr-D on AudioCaps and 16.5%\n951\ton Clotho. This suggests that caption supervision alone is\n952\tnot sufficient for learning strong audio representations in the\n953\tencoder-free setting. Using only Phase 1 pretraining performs\n954\tmuch worse, reaching 10.3% on AudioCaps and 6.3% on\n955\tClotho. This indicates that distillation pretraining alone does\n956\tnot adapt the model to the target captioning format.\n957\t\n958\t\fbest performance among all encoder-free variants. It improves\n959\tAudioCaps CIDEr-D from 43.2% to 55.4% and Clotho CIDErD from 22.3% to 27.5%, with consistent gains across other\n960\tcaptioning metrics. These results suggest that projector-level\n961\tand language-model-level distillation provide complementary\n962\tsupervision. Overall, CARD demonstrates a promising approach to encoder-free audio captioning by transferring perceptual and semantic audio knowledge into the student model\n963\tduring training, removing the need for a separate audio encoder at inference.\n964\tAI-G ENERATED C ONTENT D ISCLOSURE\n965\tThe authors used generative AI tools solely for grammar\n966\tcorrection and language refinement. No AI-generated content\n967\twas used for the development of research ideas, analysis,\n968\tinterpretation of results, or scientific conclusions. The authors\n969\treviewed and approved all revised text and take full responsibility for the content of the manuscript.\n970\tR EFERENCES\n971\t[1] C. D. Kim, B. Kim, H. Lee, and G. Kim, “AudioCaps: Generating\n972\tcaptions for audios in the wild,” in Proceedings of the 2019 Conference\n973\tof the North American Chapter of the Association for Computational\n974\tLinguistics: Human Language Technologies, Volume 1 (Long and Short\n975\tPapers), J. Burstein, C. Doran, and T. Solorio, Eds. Minneapolis,\n976\tMinnesota: Association for Computational Linguistics, Jun. 2019, pp.\n977\t119–132. [Online]. Available: https://aclanthology.org/N19-1011/\n978\t[2] K. Drossos, S. Lipping, and T. Virtanen, “Clotho: an audio captioning\n979\tdataset,” in 2020 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\n980\tSpeech and Signal Processing, ICASSP 2020, Barcelona, Spain,\n981\tMay 4-8, 2020. IEEE, 2020, pp. 736–740. [Online]. Available:\n982\thttps://doi.org/10.1109/ICASSP40776.2020.9052990\n983\t[3] B. Elizalde, S. Deshmukh, M. A. Ismail, and H. Wang, “CLAP\n984\tlearning audio concepts from natural language supervision,” in IEEE\n985\tInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n986\tICASSP 2023, Rhodes Island, Greece, June 4-10, 2023. IEEE, 2023,\n987\tpp. 1–5. [Online]. Available: https://doi.org/10.1109/ICASSP49357.20\n988\t23.10095889\n989\t[4] J. Kim, J. Jung, J. Lee, and S. H. Woo, “Enclap: Combining neural\n990\taudio codec and audio-text joint embedding for automated audio\n991\tcaptioning,” in IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech\n992\tand Signal Processing, ICASSP 2024, Seoul, Republic of Korea,\n993\tApril 14-19, 2024. IEEE, 2024, pp. 6735–6739. [Online]. Available:\n994\thttps://doi.org/10.1109/ICASSP48485.2024.10446672\n995\t[5] W. Chen, Z. Ma, X. Li, X. Xu, Y. Liang, Z. Zheng, K. Yu, and\n996\tX. Chen, “SLAM-AAC: enhancing audio captioning with paraphrasing\n997\taugmentation and clap-refine through llms,” in 2025 IEEE International\n998\tConference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing, ICASSP 2025,\n999\tHyderabad, India, April 6-11, 2025. IEEE, 2025, pp. 1–5. [Online].\n1000\tAvailable: https://doi.org/10.1109